# Architecture — Hexagonal Pattern

## Layer Flow

```
Controller → Service → Repository (port/adapter)
```

- **Controllers:** HTTP routing and input validation only. Zero business logic.
- **Services:** All business logic lives here. Injected via constructor DI.
- **Repositories:** DB access only — one per aggregate root.

## Module Isolation

No cross-module direct DB access. Call the other module's exported service.
No circular imports — if two modules need each other, extract shared logic to a common service.

```typescript
// BAD — BookingsController imports UserModel directly
import { UserModel } from '@/modules/users/user.schema';

// GOOD — BookingsService depends on UsersService via DI
import { UsersService } from '@/modules/users/users.service';
```

## DTO Rules

Every request and response has a typed DTO with `class-validator` decorators. Never return a Mongoose document from a controller — map to a response DTO first.

```typescript
// BAD — returns raw Mongoose document
@Get(':id')
async getBooking(@Param('id') id: string) {
  return this.bookingsService.findById(id);
}

// GOOD — maps to response DTO
@Get(':id')
async getBooking(@Param('id') id: string): Promise<BookingResponseDto> {
  const booking = await this.bookingsService.findById(id);
  return BookingResponseDto.fromDocument(booking);
}
```

## New Module Checklist

Every new module ships with ALL of:

- `*.module.ts`, `*.controller.ts`, `*.service.ts`
- `dto/` subfolder with request + response DTOs
- `*.schema.ts` (if DB-backed)
- Barrel `index.ts` exporting the module class

## Composition Over Inheritance

Prefer injected helper services over class extension. NestJS DI handles composition naturally — do not extend service classes.
